I"ü<p>Yahoo‚Äôs latest API is really quite cool: <a href="http://developer.yahoo.com/geo/placemaker/guide/">Placemaker</a> takes your unstructured data (e.g. any HTML page, RSS feed, etc), and extracts a nice list of <em>locations</em> that your data refers to.  It‚Äôs a brilliant tool, and I can think of quite a few ways I‚Äôd like to use it in the future.  Along with their release of a <em>ton</em> of <a href="http://developer.yahoo.com/geo/geoplanet/data/">WhereOnEarth ID codes</a> that allows you to make use of Yahoo‚Äôs various geo-services, this is a really good day to play with geocoding unstructured data.</p>

<p>So, let‚Äôs play:</p>

<p>Accessing Placemaker is simple: assuming that you‚Äôve somehow managed to <a href="http://developer.yahoo.com/wsregapp/">obtain an application id</a>, you simply make an HTTP <code class="highlighter-rouge">POST</code> request to Yahoo!‚Äôs Placemaker endpoint with a tiny bit of data specifying the nature of the data you‚Äôre dealing with, and it‚Äôs URL.  If you like <code class="highlighter-rouge">curl</code> on the command line, this might look like:</p>

<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>curl -d 'inputLanguage=en-US&amp;documentType=text/html&amp;documentURL=http://mikewest.org/&amp;appid=[APPID]' http://wherein.yahooapis.com/v1/document
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>You‚Äôll get back an XML document (RSS is also available as a response format).  Digging into the contents yields:</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Boilerplate:</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="cp">&lt;?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?&gt;</span>
<span class="nt">&lt;contentlocation</span> <span class="na">xmlns:yahoo=</span><span class="s">"http://www.yahooapis.com/v1/base.rng"</span> <span class="na">xmlns=</span><span class="s">"http://wherein.yahooapis.com/v1/schema"</span> <span class="na">xml:lang=</span><span class="s">"de-DE"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>
  <span class="nt">&lt;processingTime&gt;</span>0.380778<span class="nt">&lt;/processingTime&gt;</span>
  <span class="nt">&lt;version&gt;</span> build 090508<span class="nt">&lt;/version&gt;</span>
  <span class="nt">&lt;documentLength&gt;</span>15906<span class="nt">&lt;/documentLength&gt;</span>
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>A (list of) document element(s) containing the extracted locations:</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>  &lt;document&gt;
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>A best guess at the document‚Äôs ‚Äúscope‚Äù (the smallest region that ‚Äúbest
describes‚Äù the document):</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>    &lt;administrativeScope&gt;
      &lt;woeId&gt;20071093&lt;/woeId&gt;
      &lt;type&gt;County&lt;/type&gt;
      &lt;name&gt;&lt;![CDATA[Munich, Bavaria, DE]]&gt;&lt;/name&gt;
      &lt;centroid&gt;
        &lt;latitude&gt;48.1549&lt;/latitude&gt;
        &lt;longitude&gt;11.5417&lt;/longitude&gt;
      &lt;/centroid&gt;
    &lt;/administrativeScope&gt;
    &lt;geographicScope&gt;
      &lt;woeId&gt;29388625&lt;/woeId&gt;
      &lt;type&gt;MMA&lt;/type&gt;
      &lt;name&gt;&lt;![CDATA[MMA M√ºnchen, Bavaria, DE]]&gt;&lt;/name&gt;
      &lt;centroid&gt;
        &lt;latitude&gt;48.1549&lt;/latitude&gt;
        &lt;longitude&gt;11.5417&lt;/longitude&gt;
      &lt;/centroid&gt;
    &lt;/geographicScope&gt;
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Latitude/longitude for a bounding box that contains the places mentioned
in the document (which makes it trivial to draw an ‚Äúarea of discussion‚Äù on
a map):</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>    &lt;extents&gt;
      &lt;center&gt;
        &lt;latitude&gt;48.1364&lt;/latitude&gt;
        &lt;longitude&gt;11.5775&lt;/longitude&gt;
      &lt;/center&gt;
      &lt;southWest&gt;
        &lt;latitude&gt;48.0417&lt;/latitude&gt;
        &lt;longitude&gt;11.3771&lt;/longitude&gt;
      &lt;/southWest&gt;
      &lt;northEast&gt;
        &lt;latitude&gt;48.2292&lt;/latitude&gt;
        &lt;longitude&gt;11.749&lt;/longitude&gt;
      &lt;/northEast&gt;
    &lt;/extents&gt;
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Detailed breakdown of the places mentioned in your document, giving you
lat/long coordinates identifying the place‚Äôs center point.  Moreover, it
tells you <em>where</em> in your document the place was found (string offsets
<em>and</em> XPath expressions, to each their own).  This is helpful for those
occasions when the text you‚Äôve entered doesn‚Äôt exactly match the place‚Äôs
name that Yahoo returns (‚ÄúMunich‚Äù vs. ‚ÄúMunich, Bavaria, DE‚Äù, in this
example)  Annotating your documents with this data should be a piece of
cake.</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>    &lt;placeDetails&gt;
      &lt;place&gt;
        &lt;woeId&gt;676757&lt;/woeId&gt;
        &lt;type&gt;Town&lt;/type&gt;
        &lt;name&gt;&lt;![CDATA[Munich, Bavaria, DE]]&gt;&lt;/name&gt;
        &lt;centroid&gt;
          &lt;latitude&gt;48.1364&lt;/latitude&gt;
          &lt;longitude&gt;11.5775&lt;/longitude&gt;
        &lt;/centroid&gt;
      &lt;/place&gt;
      &lt;matchType&gt;0&lt;/matchType&gt;
      &lt;weight&gt;1&lt;/weight&gt;
      &lt;confidence&gt;7&lt;/confidence&gt;
    &lt;/placeDetails&gt;
    &lt;referenceList&gt;
      &lt;reference&gt;
        &lt;woeIds&gt;676757&lt;/woeIds&gt;
        &lt;start&gt;50&lt;/start&gt;
        &lt;end&gt;56&lt;/end&gt;
        &lt;isPlaintextMarker&gt;0&lt;/isPlaintextMarker&gt;
        &lt;text&gt;&lt;![CDATA[Munich]]&gt;&lt;/text&gt;
        &lt;type&gt;xpathwithcounts&lt;/type&gt;
        &lt;xpath&gt;&lt;![CDATA[/html[1]/body[1]/div[2]/div[1]/p[1]]]&gt;&lt;/xpath&gt;
      &lt;/reference&gt;
    &lt;/referenceList&gt;
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>And some more boilerplate.  :)</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>  &lt;/document&gt;
&lt;/contentlocation&gt;
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>Full documentation of the Placemaker <a href="http://developer.yahoo.com/geo/placemaker/guide/api_docs.html#query_parameters">query parameters</a> and <a href="http://developer.yahoo.com/geo/placemaker/guide/api-reference.html">response format</a> are available on YDN.  Christian has put together a demo of a <a href="http://isithackday.com/hacks/placemaker/">basic PHP implementation</a> (though it‚Äôs XSSable, and shouldn‚Äôt ever be used in production).</p>

<p>In general, this is <em>brilliant</em> stuff.  I‚Äôm looking forward to playing with it!</p>

